Signals that an illegal or inappropriate argument has been passed to the service. Signals that an operation has been invoked at an illegal or inappropriate time. Signals that an index of some sort (such as to an array, to a string, or to a collection) is out of range. Signals that an attribute or element contained an invalid value. Signals that an operation is not supported by the service implementation. This exception should not be confused with the 'Unimplemented' exception. The 'Unimplemented' exception is an exception that gets thrown during the development or testing phases of a service implementation, but should never be thrown in a production environment (see service contract guide for further information). Signals that a database error occurred. In order to maintain the the service encapsulation and the location transparency principle, a service consumer implementation should not attempt to parse and act upon the SQL Codes returned by this exception. The codes are intended for human consumption (e.g. the guy debugging your broken code ;-) or monitoring tools used by the operators. - The salient point here is that no business logic should ever rely on the those SQL codes, they may change any time without prior notice! Indicates service failure due to a client error. Use this type as base class for exceptions that fit this category Indicates a programming error. Use this type as base class for exceptions that fit this category. Types that derive from this type should be defined in this namespace since they are usually quite generic. Indicates resource failure. Use this type as base class for exceptions that fit this category. Types that derive from this type should be mostly defined in this namespace since they are usually quite generic. Indicates that the implementation of the service operation is not yet complete. THIS TYPE SHOULD NOT BE SUBCLASSED DIRECTLY! THIS TYPE SHOULD NOT BE SUBCLASSED DIRECTLY! Subclass ServiceException, InvariantViolationException or ResourceException instead. This corresponds typically with the portType in a WSDL THIS TYPE SHOULD NOT BE SUBCLASSED DIRECTLY! The (optional) attribute 'unmarshallingHint' can be used to give the service consumer a hint how to unmarshall the exception. Typically one would use the class name of the exception in the service implementation. - Note, this violates the service encapsulation principle (the service implementation should be transparent), it is therefore important to understand that this attribute is only a convenience feature! One must ensure (by way of unit testing) that the absence of this attribute does not impact the service consumer in any way or form! Thus, the service provider should never expect a service consumer to know what to do with the value 'java.lang.NullpointerException' in the attribute 'unmarshallingHint'. After all, the service consumer may be implemented in .NET or COBOL.

EOI- Evidence of Insurance document is also known as Proof Of Insurnace document. The service operation takes the policy number as input and processes the request for generation and delivery of EOI document using either eMail, Postal Mail.
